services:
Home Assure Plus
The Right Solutions For The Right Reasons
HOME ASSURE PLUS is an exclusive set of eight services offered by 4Sight Inspections and is included with every Home Inspection at no extra charge. You will not find this level of commitment or confidence in Home Inspection Service anywhere else.

A sample of what HOME ASSURE PLUS provides:
Re-visit*
If repairs are negotiated as a direct result of the inspection performed and the inspection report provided by 4Sight Inspections we will revisit the property at your request and at a mutually convenient time to re-inspect the contractually repaired components to ensure the repair is complete and satisfactory.

Walk-a-way***
If there are major concerns found with the inspected house that cause you to walk away from the purchase agreement I will inspect the next home you place an offer on at half price. i.e. if second home had a rate of $375 then you would only pay $185.

30 Day Warranty
We offer a 30 Day Warranty for structural and mechanical components in the home at no extra charge.

profile: Home Inspector, Home Inspection Proudly serving clients in the GTA and surrounding areas. DSM Property Services is proud to provide our clients with professional, reliable inspection services. All our inspections are conducted by a qualified and fully accredited Registered Home Inspector (RHI) and Certified Thermographer with over 25 years experience in construction and renovation. Our inspection services include: • Detailed Inspection of all visible structures and components of a home, • Infrared thermal scans* of non-visible structures and components to detect potential issues with moisture, electrical, and insulation • Use of the latest Inspection Technology • Repair and cost estimates • Recommendations and Maintenance planning • A fully detailed and easy to read report of all findings including pictures for quick reference • A reference library and links to more detailed information on the components of the home You also have the option to purchase a detailed Home History Report. *Infrared Thermal Scans are part of our premium package and are conducted to detect what the naked eye cannot. This process can identify potential problems in structure, electrical components, insulation, air leakage and moisture content. An Infrared Scan can: • help locate potential safety issues with live electrical equipment, • detect hidden heating and cooling losses, • detect moisture intrusion which could cause mould, • detect inadequate or non-existent insulation, • detect plumbing leaks and poor construction. • It could save you in potential repair costs!! Book a thermal scan inspection: * Before a warranty inspection * Before a Real Estate Investment * Before a contractor begins work * After a completed project * As part of a routine maintenance check on your home. Doing your homework on finding the right Home Inspector is crucial. You need to make sure you are hiring a qualified and experienced Inspector. After all, this person will be providing you with the information you need to make an informed decision about some very costly investments, whether it be the purchase or selling of a home, a new home renovation or existing repair, maintenance of your existing home or potential issues you are having. We hope that DSM Property Services Inc. can help you with your inspection needs! Please visit our website and our Facebook page for regular updates on home inspection and construction information! Like us on Facebook! Qualifications of the Inspector: *Graduate of the Home Inspection Training Program from Sheridan College Technical Institute with over 500 hours of formal class training *Completed Building Code and Health & Safety Training offered by the Ministry of Municipal Affairs & Housing *Accredited Level 1 Thermographer *25 + years background in Construction, experience in renovation and property management *Member of Canadian Association of Home and Property Inspectors (CAHPI) and Ontario Association of Home Inspectors (OAHI) *Current in Home Inspection training and workshops *Mentors individuals looking to enter the home inspection field

profile:
A professional inspection will significantly reduce your risk and help make the entire home buying process easier and less stressful. Legacy Home Inspections really enjoys helping our clients. In this process, customer service is our highest priority.

Legacy Home Inspections is an independently owned and operated home inspection business. We offer the highest quality of customer service in the industry. With more than 19 years of experience in the construction and home inspection industry we have performed thousands of inspections since 2004. We have the experience, training and knowledge, to provide you with the security and peace of mind you are looking for. We are proud to be your inspection service provider. Whether you are buying or selling, we can help you through the whole process with confidence. A home is the single largest investment and asset that most people own. We offer a premium service with detailed and unbiased reports to ensure that you have an accurate understanding of the subject property. We strive to continually raise the bar in the building inspection industry.

We offer more than just a look into our client's home, we also want to ensure that you know your home. Our goal is to have you understand your property. Our home inspections are intended to educate by giving you a needed understanding of the property, an overview of how the systems in the home work, how the systems of the home work in conjunction with each other, and how they should be maintained throughout the change of seasons and over the years.

Why choose Legacy Home Inspections? Because we care.

profile:
"Buying a home is expensive. Then why would you choose to put over more money if you're not required to?"

The answer is Home inspections are used to provide an opportunity for a buyer to identify any major issues with a home prior to closing. Your first clue that a home inspection is important is that it can be used as a contingency in your contract with the seller. This contingency provides that if significant defects are revealed by a home inspection, you can back out of your purchase offer, free of penalty, within a certain timeframe. The potential problems a home can have must be pretty serious if they could allow you to walk away from such a significant contract.

What ANR Home Inspection Covers:

Inspectors vary in experience, ability, and thoroughness, but a good inspector should examine certain components of the home and then produce a report covering their findings. The typical inspection lasts one to two hours and you should be present for the inspection to get a firsthand explanation of our findings and, if necessary, ask questions. Also, any problems that we uncover will make more sense if you see them in person instead of relying solely on the snapshot photos in the report.

We will note:

     Whether each problem is a safety issue, major defect, or minor defect.
     Which items need replacement and which should be repaired or serviced.
     Items that are suitable for now but that should be monitored closely.

ANR Home Inspections will even tell you about routine maintenance that should be performed, which can be a great help if you are a first-time homebuyer. 

While it is impossible to list everything we could possibly check for, the following list will give you a general idea of what to expect:

Exterior Inspection
We will complete a full inspection of the outside of the structure.

Exterior walls
We will check for damaged or missing siding, cracks and whether the soil is in excessively close contact with the bottom of the house, which can invite wood-destroying insects. However, the pest inspector (yes, you might want to engage one of those too), not the home inspector, will check for actual damage from termites, etc. We will let you know which problems are cosmetic and which could be more serious.

Foundation
If the foundation is not visible, and it usually is not, we will check for evidence of foundation issues, like cracks or settling.

Grading
We will let you know whether the grading slopes away from the house as it should. If it doesn't, water could get into the house and cause damage, and you will need to either change the slope of the yard or install a drainage system.

Garage
We will test the garage door for proper opening and closing, check the garage framing if it is visible and determine if the garage is properly ventilated (to prevent accidental carbon monoxide poisoning). If the water heater is in the garage, We will make sure it is installed high enough off the ground to minimize the risk of explosion from gasoline fumes mingling with the heater's flame.

Roof
We will check for areas where roof damage or poor installation could allow water to enter the home, such as loose, missing or improperly secured shingles and cracked or damaged mastic around vents. We will also check the condition of the gutters.

Interior Inspection
We will also complete a thorough inspection of the interior of the home. We will inspect everything from the ceiling to the cabinets under the sink.

Plumbing
We will check faucets and showers, look for visible leaks and test the water pressure. We will also identify the kind of pipes the house has if any pipes are visible and whether they need to be replaced or not. We will also identify the location of the home's main water shutoff valve.

Electrical
We will identify the kind of wiring the home has, test the outlets and make sure there are functional ground fault circuit interrupters (which can protect you from electrocution, electric shock, and electrical burns) installed in areas like the bathrooms, kitchen, garage and outdoors. We will also check your electrical panel for any safety issues and check your electrical outlets to make sure they do not present a fire hazard. We will also test the home's smoke detectors.

Heating, Ventilation, and Air Conditioning (HVAC)
We will look at your HVAC system to estimate the age of the furnace and air conditioner, determine if they function properly and recommend repairs or maintenance. We can also give you an idea of the age of the home's ducting, whether it might have leaks and if your home has sufficient insulation to minimize your energy bills.

Water heater
We will identify the age of the heater and determine if it is properly installed and secured. We will also let you know what kind of condition it is in and give you a general idea of how many years it has left.

Kitchen Appliances
We may check kitchen appliances that come with the home to make sure they work, but these are not always part of the inspection. If you think you'll want to keep them, be sure to ask which ones are not included so that you can test them yourself.

Laundry Room
We will make sure the laundry room is properly vented. A poorly maintained dryer-exhaust system can be a serious fire hazard.

Bathrooms
We will check for visible leaks, properly secured toilets, adequate ventilation, and other issues. If the bathroom does not have a window and/or a ventilation fan, mold and mildew can become problems and moisture can warp wood cabinets over time.

A home inspection will cost you a little bit of time and money, but in the long run, you'll be glad you did it. The inspection can reveal problems that you may be able to get the current owners to fix before you move in – or else, prevent you from inadvertently buying a money pit. For new home construction, it’s an imperative part of the home buying process. If you are a first-time homebuyer, an inspection can give you a crash course in home maintenance and a checklist of items that need attention to make your home as safe and sound as possible. Whatever the situation, addressing issues early through a home inspection can save you tens of thousands of dollars down the road.

Buying a home can be exciting, momentous, and meaningful. But it can also be stressful - especially if you're not sure how to gauge the physical condition of a house.

That's where the experts at Peel Home Inspections come in. While you focus on the home's style, size, layout, price, and neighborhood, we can take care of evaluating its major systems - like the plumbing, heating, and electrical. Then we'll provide you with a written report to help you make the best buying decision possible.

Making sure you have all the information before you make such a significant decision simply makes sense. Count on Peel Home Inspections to give you the unbiased, professional opinion you need, when you need it.
